WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:03.860
Hello everybody. Yes, it's my pleasure to be

2
00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:08.100
chairing this session on the necrotic tumor microenvironment as an

3
00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:11.340
instigator of metastatic aggression and immuno evasion.

4
00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:14.440
My name is Kevin Chung. I'm an associate professor at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer

5
00:00:14.500 --> 00:00:18.460
Center in Seattle, and in today's session, we're

6
00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:22.470
really going to be talking about an area that I think is of emerging interest but

7
00:00:22.500 --> 00:00:23.919
remains really poorly understood.

8
00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:27.480
It's an area of necrosis and its contributions

9
00:00:27.540 --> 00:00:30.960
to metastatic progression and

10
00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:33.960
immuno evasion. So, these are my disclosures.

11
00:00:35.020 --> 00:00:38.920
And so to set the stage, I think in the

12
00:00:38.980 --> 00:00:40.879
medical field every

13
00:00:41.700 --> 00:00:45.480
efficient scientist, every physician goes through training,

14
00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:49.530
and they read this textbook, Robbins and Kumar, "Pathologic Basics of

15
00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:53.100
Disease." And one of the first things they learn is about

16
00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:56.920
necrosis, which is this idea that a

17
00:00:56.960 --> 00:00:58.900
normal cell subject to stress

18
00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:03.720
adapts, but when it fails to adapt, it undergoes cell injury.

19
00:01:04.100 --> 00:01:06.370
And when that injury is irreversible,

20
00:01:07.340 --> 00:01:09.140
one of the outcomes is necrosis.

21
00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:13.760
So really this is the framework where we think about necrosis is

22
00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:17.740
fundamentally a pathologic process and a failure of normal

23
00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:18.520
cells to adapt.

24
00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:20.010
Now in cancer,

25
00:01:21.360 --> 00:01:24.440
necrosis is a pathologic feature of aggressive tumors.

26
00:01:25.180 --> 00:01:28.760
We know very well that you can find necrotic areas on

27
00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:32.600
scans, on MRIs, as shown here with glioblastoma,

28
00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:36.920
and these are associated with clinically worse prognoses.

29
00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:40.670
You can find it in different types of subtypes of breast cancer and other types of

30
00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:42.720
cancers. Here, like shown here, basal-like triple-negative.

31
00:01:43.350 --> 00:01:45.700
And these regions, these perinecrotic zones,

32
00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:49.440
have emerged as a significant interest.

33
00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.940
Poor prognosis, virtually all tumor types associated with fast-growing

34
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:57.720
tumors. And really, I think one of the important features is clinically we

35
00:01:57.800 --> 00:02:01.700
tend to avoid these areas for molecular studies because the

36
00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:05.640
thought process is that the tissue is dead and we should be looking for

37
00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:09.560
genetics, looking for mutations, looking for protein changes

38
00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:10.180
somewhere else.

39
00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:12.989
Now, on a cellular level,

40
00:02:14.020 --> 00:02:17.960
I believe necrosis is very well understood, in terms of the

41
00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:20.350
ultrastructural biochemical changes

42
00:02:21.200 --> 00:02:24.400
really leading to mitochondrial and membrane failure.

43
00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:28.340
So on an individual cell level, we can say that's undergoing necrosis or

44
00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.700
not. Pathologists can say that's undergoing necrosis or

45
00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:34.760
not. But I would say for the purposes of today's talk,

46
00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:39.240
at the tissue system level, tumor necrosis is far less understood.

47
00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:43.720
It really involves a variety of processes of interest to the audience here today,

48
00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:48.600
in terms of both the insults, ischemia, thrombosis, hypoxia that

49
00:02:48.680 --> 00:02:51.910
drive it, the immune mediators, neutrophils,

50
00:02:52.040 --> 00:02:55.960
macrophages, and also the different types of stressors like

51
00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.820
therptosis and other forms of cell death that may participate.

52
00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.640
We're not going to cover all of these topics in such a

53
00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:07.200
symposium today, but there's a lot of

54
00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:09.739
interest in the field to look at this more closely.

55
00:03:10.720 --> 00:03:14.360
In addition, necrosis is not simply the endpoint of cell death, but

56
00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:18.180
also spawns a variety of processes, including increased

57
00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:22.170
metastatic dissemination of CTCs, circulating tumor cells, and really nice work

58
00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:26.120
showing that this is an eco-evolutionary system that leads to clonal evolution

59
00:03:26.320 --> 00:03:27.720
and selection for metastatic clones.

60
00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:32.720
There's also been work showing that the stem and tissue sort of

61
00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:35.960
regenerative programs are activated in these regions, and there are clear

62
00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:39.920
consequences for both drug delivery, perfusion, and immune

63
00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:40.440
evasion.

64
00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:45.500
Now, in today's symposium, we're going to really have sort of all-star

65
00:03:45.620 --> 00:03:46.480
presentations from

66
00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:48.500
different perspectives.

67
00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.290
First, Jose Drover from the Francis Crick will be presenting on

68
00:03:53.320 --> 00:03:56.780
his work looking at the role of cancer-induced host

69
00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:59.100
remodeling and neutrophil plasticity.

70
00:03:59.920 --> 00:04:01.520
This will be followed by work by Dr.

71
00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:05.540
Carlos Camona Fontaine at NYU looking at the role of tumor

72
00:04:05.580 --> 00:04:08.980
immune interactions at the verge of these necrotic cores and how we can study it,

73
00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:11.540
which is really a really major gap in this area.

74
00:04:12.130 --> 00:04:12.580
And finally,

75
00:04:13.580 --> 00:04:17.579
I will be giving a talk on the role of the necrotic niche as a sculptor of the

76
00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:19.161
dissemination and metastatic process.

77
00:04:19.800 --> 00:04:23.460
So without further ado, I'm going to have Jose come up to the podium.

78
00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:26.719
Thank you.

79
00:04:33.480 --> 00:04:33.900
Okay.

80
00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:36.200
Let me stop this,

81
00:04:37.680 --> 00:04:38.220
and

82
00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:43.260
I need to stop the presentation. There you go.

83
00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:47.540
Okay. Well, thank you very much for the introduction, and thank you all for being

84
00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:51.300
here. I have no financial

85
00:04:51.310 --> 00:04:55.060
relationship to disclose. So I thought I'd first start by introducing my lab a

86
00:04:55.100 --> 00:04:58.660
little bit because I recently moved to the UK to the Francis Crick

87
00:04:58.780 --> 00:04:59.260
Institute

88
00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:03.980
a little over a year ago, where my lab is called the Cancer Macroenvironment Lab.

89
00:05:04.600 --> 00:05:07.860
And this is because we're very interested in understanding how cancer affects whole

90
00:05:07.940 --> 00:05:11.410
body physiology because growing tumors, as you know, affect a whole array of

91
00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:12.760
different physiological systems.

92
00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.040
And what usually happens is that the changes that tumors inflict to those systems

93
00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:19.500
usually loop back and fuel tumor growth.

94
00:05:20.540 --> 00:05:23.390
Now of all these different systems in the lab, we're particularly interested in how

95
00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:26.480
cancer affects the cardiovascular system, and I will show you a little bit about

96
00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:30.240
that at the end of my talk today. But also the hematopoietic and the

97
00:05:30.300 --> 00:05:34.080
immune system. Above all immune cells, we are particularly fond of neutrophils,

98
00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:35.100
which are these fellas here.

99
00:05:36.580 --> 00:05:40.540
And we're very interested also in their ability to form neutrophil extracellular

100
00:05:40.640 --> 00:05:43.820
traps, which are these structures that they form by basically dismantling their

101
00:05:43.900 --> 00:05:47.480
nuclear membrane and mixing the chromatin with the cytotoxic

102
00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:48.700
contents of their granules.

103
00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:53.500
And then they release this meter long mesh of DNA and

104
00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:56.420
cytotoxic compounds to the external world as you see here.

105
00:05:57.040 --> 00:06:00.910
And these are very cytotoxic and also very prothrombotic structures, which is going

106
00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:04.868
to be important for my talk later.Now, I'm going to start

107
00:06:04.908 --> 00:06:08.728
by telling you a bit about a project that I did when I was still a postdoc in the

108
00:06:08.748 --> 00:06:11.308
Eggebrecht lab, first at Cold Spring Harbor and then at Johns Hopkins.

109
00:06:13.128 --> 00:06:16.828
We were trying to understand a little bit better tumor necrosis, which has been

110
00:06:16.888 --> 00:06:20.448
already alluded, is an often-overlooked phenomenon that happens in most solid

111
00:06:20.508 --> 00:06:20.838
tumors,

112
00:06:21.788 --> 00:06:25.508
but is one phenomenon that is associated with bad prognosis for patients

113
00:06:25.548 --> 00:06:29.348
as was said already. This is one example in colorectal cancer

114
00:06:29.368 --> 00:06:32.208
patients, where you see that patients with a lot of necrosis fare much worse as

115
00:06:32.228 --> 00:06:34.228
patients with no necrosis in their tumors.

116
00:06:35.108 --> 00:06:39.048
And we actually recapitulated this in a cohort of breast cancer patients, where you

117
00:06:39.108 --> 00:06:42.748
again see here that these patients have a lot of necrosis in their tumors fare much

118
00:06:42.788 --> 00:06:44.328
worse in terms of recurrence-free survival.

119
00:06:44.748 --> 00:06:46.328
Same thing was true for overall survival.

120
00:06:46.738 --> 00:06:50.018
And importantly, patients with necrotic tumors have a lot more metastasis here

121
00:06:50.088 --> 00:06:51.768
measured as axillary adenopathy.

122
00:06:53.228 --> 00:06:56.848
And this was true all across the board of breast cancer subtypes.

123
00:06:56.868 --> 00:07:00.018
But one thing that we were trying to understand is what drives tumor necrosis,

124
00:07:00.068 --> 00:07:04.048
because we don't know what drives tumor necrosis beyond this rather intuitive idea

125
00:07:04.568 --> 00:07:08.248
that tumors grow very quickly, and then at some point, the innermost core central

126
00:07:08.308 --> 00:07:10.688
regions of the tumor become hypoxic and then necrotic.

127
00:07:11.448 --> 00:07:14.688
And I'll try to argue that this is not necessarily always the case.

128
00:07:15.948 --> 00:07:19.828
Now, instead, what we find is that neutrophils can aggregate

129
00:07:19.888 --> 00:07:22.308
within the vessels of the tumor, microvasculature,

130
00:07:23.268 --> 00:07:26.728
and they can form nets within the vessels of the tumor.

131
00:07:27.368 --> 00:07:31.068
Now, these nets are highly prothrombotic structures, so what they're doing in the

132
00:07:31.108 --> 00:07:34.328
end by aggregating within the vasculature is blocking the blood flow in that

133
00:07:34.388 --> 00:07:38.348
particular vascular branch, and that leads to downstream hypoxia and then later

134
00:07:38.388 --> 00:07:40.468
on to necrosis. And this is something that you can see here.

135
00:07:41.278 --> 00:07:42.648
And these are 41

136
00:07:43.968 --> 00:07:44.288
tumors,

137
00:07:45.128 --> 00:07:47.328
and we injected a vascular dye to these mice here in red.

138
00:07:47.368 --> 00:07:50.708
So to show vessels which are perfused, the vessels not perfused in green, and the

139
00:07:50.748 --> 00:07:51.568
neutrophils in cyan.

140
00:07:52.408 --> 00:07:55.678
And we very often find vessels like this one, as you can see, is perfused, and then

141
00:07:55.708 --> 00:07:59.148
at some point, perfusion stops. And where perfusion stops, we

142
00:07:59.208 --> 00:08:02.748
invariably find one of these big intraluminal neutrophil

143
00:08:02.788 --> 00:08:03.368
aggregates.

144
00:08:04.188 --> 00:08:06.748
So there's perfusion, then we have the neutrophil aggregate, and from that point

145
00:08:06.788 --> 00:08:08.528
downstream, there is no perfusion anymore.

146
00:08:10.108 --> 00:08:12.728
Now, why are neutrophils doing this?

147
00:08:13.448 --> 00:08:17.228
Well, to cut a long story short, what we found basically is that the

148
00:08:17.288 --> 00:08:20.628
tumor is remotely communicating with the hematopoietic compartment in the bone

149
00:08:20.688 --> 00:08:20.908
marrow

150
00:08:22.148 --> 00:08:24.648
and is inducing a myeloid skew of hematopoiesis.

151
00:08:24.668 --> 00:08:28.318
It's inducing the increased production of the granulocyte/monocyte progenitors and

152
00:08:28.348 --> 00:08:31.488
a systemic increase in neutrophils all over the place.

153
00:08:31.508 --> 00:08:35.108
But it's also inducing the appearance of a new population of neutrophils, which

154
00:08:35.148 --> 00:08:37.889
have low levels of L6C, these L6Clow neutrophils.

155
00:08:38.668 --> 00:08:42.308
And these neutrophils have two very interesting characteristics, in my opinion.

156
00:08:42.348 --> 00:08:46.048
The first one is that these L6Clow neutrophils don't

157
00:08:46.088 --> 00:08:48.588
extravasate towards inflammatory stimuli.

158
00:08:49.128 --> 00:08:53.068
This is what you can see here in a classical peritonitis model, where we can find

159
00:08:53.088 --> 00:08:54.588
these L6Clow neutrophils in blood.

160
00:08:54.957 --> 00:08:57.708
They're completely absent in the peritoneal lavage, and we confirmed this using

161
00:08:57.748 --> 00:09:01.308
intravital microscopy as well. So that's why we call these neutrophils, these

162
00:09:01.448 --> 00:09:04.428
L6Clow neutrophils, we call them vascular restricted neutrophils because they are

163
00:09:04.448 --> 00:09:06.788
restricted to the vascular space, and they cannot leave.

164
00:09:07.728 --> 00:09:11.248
The other thing these neutrophils do very differently is that they form a lot more

165
00:09:11.308 --> 00:09:13.468
NETs than the normal neutrophils from the same host.

166
00:09:14.128 --> 00:09:18.088
And actually NETs, we found out are actually very important

167
00:09:18.128 --> 00:09:21.668
for this process of necrosis, because when you have tumors in mice that are

168
00:09:21.688 --> 00:09:23.708
genetically unable to form necrosis,

169
00:09:24.628 --> 00:09:28.188
then necrosis in these tumors is greatly reduced. Sorry.

170
00:09:29.768 --> 00:09:31.888
And this is showing what I think it's a very

171
00:09:32.708 --> 00:09:36.648
interesting thing, which is that tumor necrosis is not necessarily

172
00:09:36.708 --> 00:09:40.588
a passive phenomenon. It can actually be an active phenomenon driven by

173
00:09:40.628 --> 00:09:43.808
neutrophils, and in particular by neutrophils forming NETs in the luminal

174
00:09:43.818 --> 00:09:46.248
compartment of the vasculature of those tumors.

175
00:09:47.108 --> 00:09:50.668
And that is important because, as was alluded already, tumor necrosis is

176
00:09:50.728 --> 00:09:53.308
associated with bad prognosis across the board of cancer types.

177
00:09:53.408 --> 00:09:57.068
Now, if you think that tumor necrosis is a passive phenomenon, that there's

178
00:09:57.128 --> 00:09:58.987
basically not much you can do about it.

179
00:09:59.448 --> 00:10:02.628
But now that we know that it's an active phenomenon, at least in some cases driven

180
00:10:02.648 --> 00:10:06.328
by the neutrophils, it means that we can target that phenomenon, and we can

181
00:10:06.368 --> 00:10:08.268
reduce tumor necrosis. And when we do that,

182
00:10:09.128 --> 00:10:12.788
when we target the NETs, we reduce tumor necrosis, but we also

183
00:10:12.808 --> 00:10:15.468
reduce metastasis. We reduce metastatic spread.

184
00:10:16.828 --> 00:10:19.268
Now, we confirmed this using various other means.

185
00:10:19.308 --> 00:10:21.207
So, for instance, here you see if your mice

186
00:10:22.147 --> 00:10:24.928
are neutropenic, if you don't have neutrophils, this is in the Lewis lung model,

187
00:10:26.228 --> 00:10:27.828
then your tumors are not too necrotic.

188
00:10:28.408 --> 00:10:31.998
If you treat mice with disulfiram, this is the G2 untapped genetic spontaneous

189
00:10:32.048 --> 00:10:32.288
model.

190
00:10:34.008 --> 00:10:37.568
And we published a couple of years ago that disulfiram is a drug that is able to

191
00:10:37.588 --> 00:10:41.488
block NETs very efficiently. Then you can also reduce tumor necrosis.

192
00:10:41.588 --> 00:10:45.378
Same thing is true if you block with TI05 and neutrophil platelet interactions,

193
00:10:45.408 --> 00:10:49.088
which are very important for the initiation of NETs within the luminal compartment.

194
00:10:49.628 --> 00:10:51.908
You can also reduce tumor necrosis in this case.

195
00:10:52.348 --> 00:10:56.128
And if you treat your mice with DNase 1, which is able to degrade the NETs once

196
00:10:56.148 --> 00:10:56.708
they've been formed,

197
00:10:57.568 --> 00:11:00.008
that also reduces tumor necrosis.

198
00:11:00.028 --> 00:11:03.968
And in all of these cases where we looked at lung metastatic spread, we saw a

199
00:11:04.008 --> 00:11:05.688
decrease in lung metastasis.

200
00:11:07.068 --> 00:11:07.788
Now, why is that?

201
00:11:09.328 --> 00:11:13.088
Again, I'm cutting a long story short, but what we found basically is that when you

202
00:11:13.148 --> 00:11:15.948
have necrosis, well, you're not going to have

203
00:11:16.728 --> 00:11:20.227
viable cancer cells in that area. But what you also generate is this

204
00:11:20.288 --> 00:11:21.888
perinecrotic region

205
00:11:22.928 --> 00:11:26.768
around the necrotic area where we find that cancer cells are changing and

206
00:11:26.828 --> 00:11:29.268
gaining pro-metastatic features. So here's one example.

207
00:11:29.428 --> 00:11:33.347
You can see here how vimentin is nicely expressed around these

208
00:11:33.448 --> 00:11:36.788
perinecrotic regions. And more generally, when we have a look at the terms which

209
00:11:36.848 --> 00:11:40.658
are upregulated in perinecrotic regions compared to the non-necrotic regions of

210
00:11:40.688 --> 00:11:41.148
these tumors,

211
00:11:42.128 --> 00:11:44.608
we find many terms related to hypoxia, EMT, and migration.

212
00:11:45.248 --> 00:11:48.688
Many TGF-beta pathways, epithelial to mesenchymal transition pathways,

213
00:11:49.268 --> 00:11:50.748
and epithelial cell migration pathways.

214
00:11:50.788 --> 00:11:54.728
So it seems like specifically in these perinecrotic regions of the tumor, cancer

215
00:11:54.768 --> 00:11:56.728
cells are gaining these pro-metastatic traits.

216
00:11:57.528 --> 00:12:01.278
And we show in the paper that TGF-beta is actually critical for these processes,

217
00:12:01.948 --> 00:12:04.888
necrosis enhanced metastatic spreadSo I'm going to

218
00:12:04.908 --> 00:12:08.888
stop here with this story because it's already published and you can have

219
00:12:08.908 --> 00:12:12.528
a look there. But in general terms, what we found was that the tumor is

220
00:12:12.548 --> 00:12:15.798
communicating remotely with the bone marrow, changing bone marrow dynamics,

221
00:12:16.828 --> 00:12:19.318
increasing the production of neutrophils, and making

222
00:12:20.348 --> 00:12:23.868
a new population of neutrophils that was not described before appear, these LY6C

223
00:12:23.948 --> 00:12:27.668
low neutrophils, which are restricted to the vasculature and can

224
00:12:27.768 --> 00:12:31.568
aggregate within the luminal space, block the blood flow, and cause downstream

225
00:12:31.608 --> 00:12:35.248
regions of tumor to become hypoxic first and then necrotic,

226
00:12:36.208 --> 00:12:39.748
and that in turn generate this perinecrotic area around it where through

227
00:12:39.768 --> 00:12:43.448
TGF-beta we have this phenotype that increases metastatic spread.

228
00:12:45.168 --> 00:12:49.068
Now, I'm going to switch now to show you some of the projects which

229
00:12:49.108 --> 00:12:51.408
are ongoing in the lab at the moment.

230
00:12:51.928 --> 00:12:55.568
Bear in mind, my lab is still very young. I've been there for a little over a year.

231
00:12:56.088 --> 00:12:59.348
But I want to show you a little bit about what we're doing in terms of the cancer

232
00:12:59.428 --> 00:13:03.348
cardiovascular disease interplay, because it correlates, we believe, with these

233
00:13:03.428 --> 00:13:07.228
neutrophils that we find are causing necrosis. Now, why are we interested in this?

234
00:13:08.048 --> 00:13:09.068
Well, we're interested because

235
00:13:10.308 --> 00:13:13.718
cancer patients have a lot more cardiovascular disease than the general population,

236
00:13:13.798 --> 00:13:17.748
and here are some examples. Myocardial infarction, much higher mortality

237
00:13:17.788 --> 00:13:21.008
in cancer patients. Same thing for an incidence of stroke, and of course,

238
00:13:21.048 --> 00:13:24.228
thrombosis, which is one of the main problems that we have clinically

239
00:13:24.668 --> 00:13:26.228
when treating these patients.

240
00:13:27.148 --> 00:13:30.248
Now, we're looking into this in three different angles.

241
00:13:30.288 --> 00:13:33.888
The first one is trying to understand how cancer affects the heart directly,

242
00:13:34.348 --> 00:13:37.148
how it affects thrombosis, and how it affects atherosclerosis.

243
00:13:38.168 --> 00:13:40.328
But I'm going to be talking today mostly about

244
00:13:41.168 --> 00:13:42.248
how cancer affects the heart.

245
00:13:43.688 --> 00:13:47.548
So research on

246
00:13:47.588 --> 00:13:51.248
this area is focusing nowadays mostly on how

247
00:13:51.308 --> 00:13:55.008
cancer treatments affect the cardiovascular health and the heart in

248
00:13:55.028 --> 00:13:58.468
particular, because many cancer treatments are cardiotoxic directly.

249
00:13:58.488 --> 00:14:01.978
But when you look at the clinical literature, you see that

250
00:14:02.008 --> 00:14:05.568
treatment-naive patients are also at much higher risk of cardiovascular disease.

251
00:14:05.648 --> 00:14:09.068
So what we believe is that there must be something beyond cancer treatment that is

252
00:14:09.128 --> 00:14:10.448
affecting cardiovascular health.

253
00:14:11.868 --> 00:14:15.708
And in that sense, we believe that these LY6C low vascular restricted neutrophils

254
00:14:15.728 --> 00:14:19.448
that we found in our cancer models, which are restricted to the vasculature and

255
00:14:19.528 --> 00:14:23.448
highly reactive within the vessels, and which also interact more with platelets

256
00:14:23.488 --> 00:14:27.368
and fibrin, these neutrophils are in a good position to be able to

257
00:14:27.388 --> 00:14:30.968
explain the high burden of cardiovascular disease in these cancer patients.

258
00:14:32.608 --> 00:14:35.728
Why is that? Well, because as I showed you at the beginning, they can aggregate

259
00:14:35.788 --> 00:14:38.958
within the vessels of the tumor, and they can block the blood flow there, but

260
00:14:38.968 --> 00:14:42.598
there's nothing in principle that will stop them from doing that

261
00:14:42.688 --> 00:14:45.568
outside of the tumor, potentially in the coronary arteries.

262
00:14:45.608 --> 00:14:49.448
And this is actually what we see. This is in the 4T1 model, and this is a heart,

263
00:14:50.068 --> 00:14:51.748
and this is a coronary artery on the heart.

264
00:14:51.808 --> 00:14:55.228
And what we're seeing is that neutrophils can also aggregate within the

265
00:14:55.268 --> 00:14:57.468
vasculature of the heart in this particular case,

266
00:14:58.448 --> 00:15:02.288
and they can form aggregates, and there's also fibrin in these regions and so

267
00:15:02.368 --> 00:15:06.228
on. Here's another example. This is a big aggregate of neutrophils in the

268
00:15:06.288 --> 00:15:10.248
heart with some fibrin. What I would like to point your attention to in this image

269
00:15:10.308 --> 00:15:14.228
is this area here, where you see there's a lot of these neutrophils crawling

270
00:15:14.288 --> 00:15:18.208
around the vessels of the heart, and there's a reduction in the profusion in that

271
00:15:18.248 --> 00:15:19.208
particular area.

272
00:15:20.128 --> 00:15:20.258
Now,

273
00:15:21.428 --> 00:15:25.108
the other interesting observation that we have is that neutrophils can form nets in

274
00:15:25.168 --> 00:15:28.828
the hearts of these mice, and this is interesting because we haven't done

275
00:15:28.888 --> 00:15:30.038
anything to the hearts of these mice.

276
00:15:30.098 --> 00:15:33.428
So these mice have a tumor, and that's it, and then we see these neutrophils

277
00:15:33.548 --> 00:15:36.048
forming nets in the heart of these mice.

278
00:15:36.948 --> 00:15:40.898
And we know that nets are important drivers of damage in the heart, and

279
00:15:40.928 --> 00:15:41.968
this is one example here.

280
00:15:43.308 --> 00:15:47.188
In acute myocardial infarction, they are drivers of damage because if you block

281
00:15:47.228 --> 00:15:50.228
them with chloramine, or if you degrade the nets with DNase,

282
00:15:51.188 --> 00:15:54.648
we can reduce by roughly one-third the amount of

283
00:15:55.148 --> 00:15:58.888
dead myocardium. So nets are drivers of acute myocardial infarction.

284
00:15:59.468 --> 00:16:01.428
So what's going on in our tumor models?

285
00:16:01.628 --> 00:16:01.768
So

286
00:16:03.128 --> 00:16:06.988
this is in the 4T1 model. We implant the tumor, and then we were started to look at

287
00:16:07.028 --> 00:16:10.848
the heart in these mice. And what we see is that as the

288
00:16:10.888 --> 00:16:14.288
tumor progressed, the number of these vascular restricted neutrophils, which start

289
00:16:14.348 --> 00:16:17.748
crawling around the vasculature of the heart, increases, and that

290
00:16:17.808 --> 00:16:20.608
coincides with an increase on heart fibrosis.

291
00:16:21.888 --> 00:16:25.228
And again, this is very interesting for us because, again, we haven't done anything

292
00:16:25.248 --> 00:16:29.028
to these hearts. These mice have a tumor, and the heart is becoming fibrotic

293
00:16:29.388 --> 00:16:30.128
as a result.

294
00:16:31.468 --> 00:16:34.288
We find the same in another model. This is the Lewis Lung model.

295
00:16:34.318 --> 00:16:37.988
At endpoint, we also have increased cardiac fibrosis in this model.

296
00:16:39.408 --> 00:16:39.538
Now,

297
00:16:40.348 --> 00:16:43.528
the next thing we ask is whether these changes that we're seeing in fibrosis are

298
00:16:43.548 --> 00:16:46.208
somehow affecting the function of these hearts.

299
00:16:46.928 --> 00:16:50.448
So we did MRI imaging to assess the functional status of the hearts in these mice.

300
00:16:51.528 --> 00:16:55.128
And what we see is basically this. So as tumors progress,

301
00:16:55.328 --> 00:16:58.808
the end systolic volume is increasing, so the leftover

302
00:16:58.828 --> 00:17:02.148
blood after systole is increasing, which means that the

303
00:17:02.588 --> 00:17:04.508
heart isn't able to pump all of the blood

304
00:17:06.388 --> 00:17:10.248
it contains. And that's why the ejection fraction is coming down.

305
00:17:10.268 --> 00:17:13.378
So the contractile performance of the heart is declining,

306
00:17:14.189 --> 00:17:17.929
but the heart is at the moment compensating by increasing the volume at

307
00:17:17.988 --> 00:17:21.949
end-diastolic. So the heart is compensated by getting more

308
00:17:21.988 --> 00:17:23.788
blood in before it contracts.

309
00:17:25.429 --> 00:17:29.328
And therefore, the cardiac output is for now maintained in these mice.

310
00:17:29.888 --> 00:17:33.428
But this comes with a cost, and the left ventricular mass is actually increasing.

311
00:17:33.448 --> 00:17:37.348
So there's a structural remodeling, and there are functional changes in the

312
00:17:37.388 --> 00:17:41.168
heart of these mice. So heart function is indeed affected by growing tumors

313
00:17:41.248 --> 00:17:42.508
independently of treatment.

314
00:17:44.388 --> 00:17:47.808
So what we're seeing is consistent with human heart failure progression.

315
00:17:47.888 --> 00:17:51.808
We're seeing this fibrosis and a progressive left ventricular remodeling with

316
00:17:51.928 --> 00:17:55.408
worsening systolic emptying, and also, I didn't show you, but there's slower

317
00:17:55.428 --> 00:17:57.548
filling and ejection dynamics in these hearts.

318
00:17:58.528 --> 00:18:02.058
Now, the forward output, the cardiac output of the heart is still maintained

319
00:18:02.668 --> 00:18:04.288
because the heart is compensating.

320
00:18:04.318 --> 00:18:07.488
This is called Frank-Starling preload compensation, and it's something that

321
00:18:07.548 --> 00:18:11.148
typically happens in humans as well, but it's a compensation that will not last

322
00:18:11.188 --> 00:18:15.158
forever. It will eventually decompensate.So this is what we know

323
00:18:15.238 --> 00:18:16.438
so far. We know that

324
00:18:17.638 --> 00:18:21.078
in cancer, we have neutrophils forming NETs in the heart, we have neutrophils

325
00:18:21.178 --> 00:18:24.418
aggregating in the vasculature of the heart, and we have

326
00:18:24.478 --> 00:18:27.968
changes in the heart fibrosis and function.

327
00:18:28.918 --> 00:18:31.388
Now, we still don't know whether this is driven by neutrophils or NETs.

328
00:18:31.408 --> 00:18:33.808
So hopefully, I'll be able to tell you more about this in the future.

329
00:18:34.628 --> 00:18:37.748
And whether cardiovascular events in cancer patients correlate with the presence of

330
00:18:37.798 --> 00:18:41.408
NETs also, and most importantly, whether we can

331
00:18:41.438 --> 00:18:45.148
prevent this by pharmacologically blocking NETs

332
00:18:45.418 --> 00:18:46.598
upon cancer diagnosis.

333
00:18:47.938 --> 00:18:51.118
And then I'm going to switch to another project that I would like to tell you a bit

334
00:18:51.198 --> 00:18:55.088
about. It has to do with this vascular-restricted neutrophil,

335
00:18:55.138 --> 00:18:58.098
this Ly6C low neutrophil. So what are they doing? Where do they come from?

336
00:18:58.878 --> 00:19:02.778
And we're finding that these neutrophils may represent an oncofetal reversion of

337
00:19:02.818 --> 00:19:04.978
neutrophil programs in cancer.

338
00:19:06.047 --> 00:19:08.958
So this started from a completely different project, where we were looking at

339
00:19:08.998 --> 00:19:12.978
neutrophils in the embryos, because neutrophils are present in developing embryos

340
00:19:12.998 --> 00:19:15.318
around mid-gestation. You can see them here. There's lots of them.

341
00:19:15.338 --> 00:19:19.278
They are enlarged so that you can see them, lots of them in the liver, and

342
00:19:19.318 --> 00:19:23.038
there's also aggregates of these neutrophils here and there all over the body.

343
00:19:24.118 --> 00:19:27.618
Now, we were looking into this because neutrophils show remarkable plasticity

344
00:19:27.678 --> 00:19:31.098
during embryonic development, and they change a lot across embryonic time,

345
00:19:32.658 --> 00:19:35.818
both at the level of the hematopoietic stem and progenitor cells and also of the

346
00:19:35.858 --> 00:19:37.998
mature neutrophils. The mature neutrophils, you have them here.

347
00:19:39.038 --> 00:19:42.678
Around mid-gestation, there's a population of neutrophils that comes up here

348
00:19:43.158 --> 00:19:45.998
that we are studying, and we're very interested in understanding what they are

349
00:19:46.038 --> 00:19:49.918
doing. But the interesting thing comes that when we were looking at the

350
00:19:49.978 --> 00:19:53.738
neutrophils of these embryos, what we found was that these

351
00:19:53.838 --> 00:19:57.538
Ly6C low neutrophils that we find in the context of cancer

352
00:19:57.598 --> 00:20:00.758
appear naturally during embryonic development.

353
00:20:00.918 --> 00:20:04.358
So they are there around mid-gestation, and then upon birth, they

354
00:20:04.398 --> 00:20:06.978
disappear completely. And we don't see them again.

355
00:20:07.198 --> 00:20:10.158
So these vascular-restricted neutrophils, they apparently appear naturally during

356
00:20:10.198 --> 00:20:13.458
embryonic development. Then we lose them after birth, and they don't appear again

357
00:20:13.538 --> 00:20:17.438
unless you have a tumor where this population comes out again.

358
00:20:18.718 --> 00:20:21.858
This is just to show you that these are really neutrophils because we sorted them.

359
00:20:23.077 --> 00:20:26.988
Now, the next question is: how similar are these embryonic Ly6C low

360
00:20:27.018 --> 00:20:29.178
neutrophils to the ones that we find in cancer?

361
00:20:29.218 --> 00:20:29.338
Well,

362
00:20:30.198 --> 00:20:34.058
what we did here was to have a look at the genes which are upregulated or

363
00:20:34.138 --> 00:20:37.738
downregulated in these Ly6C low neutrophils that we find in cancer and

364
00:20:37.818 --> 00:20:41.238
compare them with the Ly6C low neutrophils that we find during development.

365
00:20:41.898 --> 00:20:45.058
And as you can see here, most of the genes which are upregulated are still

366
00:20:45.118 --> 00:20:48.518
upregulated. Most of the genes which are downregulated are still downregulated.

367
00:20:48.958 --> 00:20:52.418
So there's a remarkable similarity between these neutrophils that we find in the

368
00:20:52.478 --> 00:20:55.138
embryo and the neutrophils that we find in cancer.

369
00:20:55.198 --> 00:20:59.038
Actually, there's over 70% concordance in the genes that are going up or

370
00:20:59.078 --> 00:21:00.958
down in both cases.

371
00:21:01.878 --> 00:21:05.838
So we are thinking is that these cancer-elicited Ly6C low neutrophils represent

372
00:21:05.878 --> 00:21:09.238
a tumor-induced reversion of hematopoiesis to a

373
00:21:09.298 --> 00:21:12.898
mid-gestational program that includes the production of these

374
00:21:12.938 --> 00:21:14.378
vascular-restricted neutrophils.

375
00:21:15.798 --> 00:21:18.948
So now we're very interested in understanding what are the embryonic features of

376
00:21:18.978 --> 00:21:22.378
these neutrophils because we believe that that is going to help us understand what

377
00:21:22.458 --> 00:21:24.238
are they doing in the context of cancer.

378
00:21:25.158 --> 00:21:28.598
And they have many different things that they do differently, many related to

379
00:21:28.658 --> 00:21:32.418
angiogenesis, lots of developmental pathways, neural pathways,

380
00:21:32.718 --> 00:21:35.298
cartilage, bone development, matrix organization.

381
00:21:36.918 --> 00:21:38.957
And I'll just show you a couple of examples here.

382
00:21:39.018 --> 00:21:39.138
So

383
00:21:39.938 --> 00:21:43.878
these Ly6C low neutrophils, when it comes to angiogenesis, they show

384
00:21:43.918 --> 00:21:47.558
a shift from a more classical inflammatory neutrophil angiogenesis

385
00:21:47.658 --> 00:21:51.338
program with a classical ECM degrading, ECM opening, and the inflammatory

386
00:21:51.358 --> 00:21:53.388
angiogenetic neutrophil effector phenotype.

387
00:21:54.058 --> 00:21:57.608
And they move to a vascular patterning, endothelial

388
00:21:57.738 --> 00:22:01.338
guidance, junction organization, remodeling program.

389
00:22:02.698 --> 00:22:06.558
So these Ly6C low neutrophils in the context of the embryo and in cancer

390
00:22:06.618 --> 00:22:08.798
can potentially influence vascular organization.

391
00:22:08.898 --> 00:22:11.898
This is something that we're looking now in the context of cancer to see whether

392
00:22:11.938 --> 00:22:15.338
these neutrophils are doing something regarding vascular patterning there.

393
00:22:16.618 --> 00:22:19.378
The other thing I would like to point out here is whether when you look at the

394
00:22:19.438 --> 00:22:23.038
genes related to the interaction of these neutrophils to the

395
00:22:23.898 --> 00:22:27.498
vascular walls, we also see an interesting shift

396
00:22:27.538 --> 00:22:31.278
between a more classical inflammatory interaction program

397
00:22:31.898 --> 00:22:35.438
driven by selectins and in beta-2 integrins to a

398
00:22:36.098 --> 00:22:39.858
program that has more to do with a stable wall interaction, beta-1

399
00:22:39.898 --> 00:22:41.058
integrin-dependent adhesion,

400
00:22:42.178 --> 00:22:45.708
including fibronectin receptors and these other integrin, which is

401
00:22:45.778 --> 00:22:48.698
also binding laminin as well as fibronectin.

402
00:22:49.338 --> 00:22:50.778
So these

403
00:22:51.978 --> 00:22:55.118
Ly6C low neutrophils in the embryo as well as in cancer, they're gaining genes

404
00:22:55.158 --> 00:22:58.668
associated with this beta-1 substrate engagement and

405
00:22:58.978 --> 00:23:00.318
more stable interaction.

406
00:23:01.498 --> 00:23:05.318
So what we're thinking is that these Ly6C low neutrophils in development are

407
00:23:05.338 --> 00:23:09.018
an endothelial guidance and patterning population that is programmed to

408
00:23:09.078 --> 00:23:11.818
form stable interactions at the vessel wall.

409
00:23:12.438 --> 00:23:15.078
Now in cancer, they appear again.

410
00:23:15.998 --> 00:23:19.678
And what happens is that we believe is that they're suddenly exposed to

411
00:23:19.698 --> 00:23:23.067
pro-inflammatory stimuli, which would otherwise be completely

412
00:23:23.067 --> 00:23:26.738
absent in the embryo, which is in a sterile environment.

413
00:23:26.838 --> 00:23:30.448
So they are unable to extravasate, but they remain able to form NETs, and they

414
00:23:30.498 --> 00:23:34.098
respond by forming these NETs that then drive thromboinflammatory

415
00:23:34.108 --> 00:23:35.658
occlusion, tumor necrosis

416
00:23:37.218 --> 00:23:37.578
in the end.

417
00:23:38.478 --> 00:23:40.988
So we're currently exploring how the developmental programs of these

418
00:23:40.998 --> 00:23:43.598
vascular-restricted neutrophils can shape tumor progression.

419
00:23:44.358 --> 00:23:47.798
And one of the genes that I'll point out here that we find downregulated,

420
00:23:47.918 --> 00:23:51.698
both in the embryonic Ly6C low neutrophils as well as in the cancer Ly6C low

421
00:23:51.708 --> 00:23:53.688
neutrophils, is CD177.

422
00:23:54.558 --> 00:23:58.148
And of interest to this audience may be to attend Sepideh Golami's talk on

423
00:23:58.178 --> 00:24:01.618
Tuesday because she's going to be talking about this molecule in particular and how

424
00:24:01.638 --> 00:24:05.268
NET inhibition relates to necrosis reduction in colorectal cancer and

425
00:24:05.298 --> 00:24:06.678
colorectal cancer metastasis.

426
00:24:07.958 --> 00:24:08.418
And with that,

427
00:24:09.338 --> 00:24:12.918
these are the people in the lab. Most of the work that I've shown you today was

428
00:24:12.958 --> 00:24:14.718
done by Saira, Afshan, or Nathan.

429
00:24:15.578 --> 00:24:19.318
And these are my collaborators, funding sources, and I'll thank you for

430
00:24:19.538 --> 00:24:20.258
your attention. Thank

431
00:24:20.298 --> 00:24:29.988
you.Oh,

432
00:24:30.048 --> 00:24:30.488
got you. Sure.

433
00:24:32.988 --> 00:24:36.668
Hi. You're proposing that these

434
00:24:36.708 --> 00:24:40.028
neutrophils occur from altered hematopoiesis.

435
00:24:40.548 --> 00:24:44.488
Do you think that's at all related to emergency myelopoiesis

436
00:24:44.508 --> 00:24:45.448
and sort of related,

437
00:24:46.588 --> 00:24:50.548
do you think you can mimic the Ly6C low

438
00:24:50.628 --> 00:24:53.848
neutrophils with a common infection or something like that?

439
00:24:54.748 --> 00:24:57.688
So we think that emergency myelopoiesis is going to be involved, but

440
00:24:57.708 --> 00:25:01.408
we think that is not sufficient. So common

441
00:25:01.468 --> 00:25:04.808
infection, for instance, we look for them in sepsis and we cannot find them.

442
00:25:05.148 --> 00:25:07.608
So it's not an easy population to find.

443
00:25:08.368 --> 00:25:08.508
Now,

444
00:25:09.348 --> 00:25:12.368
I would say that when you look at the progenitors in these

445
00:25:13.268 --> 00:25:13.868
tumor-bearing mice,

446
00:25:14.928 --> 00:25:18.848
there's an upregulation of CPP beta, which is a known driver of

447
00:25:18.948 --> 00:25:22.548
emergency myelopoiesis. So we believe that emergency myelopoiesis may be

448
00:25:22.728 --> 00:25:26.488
necessary but not sufficient to make these neutrophils appear.

449
00:25:29.128 --> 00:25:32.828
Hi, a very nice talk. You show a very nice correlation

450
00:25:32.948 --> 00:25:36.748
between an increase in fibrosis and an increase in the

451
00:25:36.808 --> 00:25:38.788
recruitment of neutrophils. So,

452
00:25:39.668 --> 00:25:43.568
I wonder if in your model you also have a mechanistic understanding of if

453
00:25:43.608 --> 00:25:46.988
there is a mechanistic connection between these two processes, and in particular,

454
00:25:47.288 --> 00:25:50.898
if the release of collagen fragments that arises during

455
00:25:51.508 --> 00:25:55.388
fibrosis can also attract or help this recruitment of neutrophils.

456
00:25:55.468 --> 00:25:57.968
Yeah, so that's a really good question.

457
00:25:58.048 --> 00:26:01.627
The short answer is we don't know. So we just started working on this.

458
00:26:02.808 --> 00:26:04.848
But we're working on what the mechanism is at the moment.

459
00:26:05.188 --> 00:26:08.928
So hopefully next time I'll be able to... Yeah.

460
00:26:09.028 --> 00:26:11.928
So thank you very much for the talk. Fantastic pictures.

461
00:26:12.028 --> 00:26:15.568
I had a question about sort of the size of the vessels that these

462
00:26:15.608 --> 00:26:19.578
microemboli could target. Are we solely looking at capillary beds, or are they

463
00:26:19.648 --> 00:26:23.428
able to target much bigger? And if so, do we have a

464
00:26:23.448 --> 00:26:26.548
sense of what that size limit is and if they pass into the venous system?

465
00:26:27.108 --> 00:26:27.628
Yeah. So,

466
00:26:28.468 --> 00:26:31.628
we did look at the size of these obstructions.

467
00:26:32.528 --> 00:26:34.647
We don't see them only in very small capillaries.

468
00:26:34.707 --> 00:26:37.608
We see them in vessels up to 100 microns in diameter.

469
00:26:38.268 --> 00:26:38.568
So,

470
00:26:39.968 --> 00:26:43.548
as far as we can tell, it can happen in all sorts of different

471
00:26:43.568 --> 00:26:47.448
ranges of vessels. The point is that once

472
00:26:47.488 --> 00:26:51.068
the neutrophil and the platelet, which are important for this process, start

473
00:26:51.668 --> 00:26:55.608
interacting and inducing this net formation, there's a feed-forward loop

474
00:26:55.648 --> 00:26:59.527
that I think will basically cover at least up to 100 micrometer

475
00:27:00.168 --> 00:27:00.688
diameters.

476
00:27:01.168 --> 00:27:04.888
And to clarify, this is primarily in the outgoing

477
00:27:04.928 --> 00:27:07.328
arterial system. Do we see these in venous structures?

478
00:27:08.308 --> 00:27:09.188
We did not look

