neighbors, they acquire different abilities such as multitasking,

972
00:55:58.724 --> 00:56:02.404
redundancy, the ability to form self-generated gradients, and the ability to be

973
00:56:02.584 --> 00:56:04.944
stable despite fluctuating cues.

974
00:56:05.004 --> 00:56:08.904
And these require a variety of homotypic and heterotypic adhesion

975
00:56:08.964 --> 00:56:12.624
systems, cell-cell interactions that allow for very

976
00:56:12.704 --> 00:56:14.684
complicated multicellular behavior.

977
00:56:16.544 --> 00:56:17.864
For example, one area that we

978
00:56:19.224 --> 00:56:22.864
showed a while back was that tumor cell clusters, when you drill down into their

979
00:56:22.924 --> 00:56:26.324
sort of intracellular structure by electron microscopy, contain these intracellular

980
00:56:26.364 --> 00:56:30.304
channels. These intracellular channels, in fact, harbor an accumulation of growth

981
00:56:30.364 --> 00:56:33.444
factors, in this case, epigen, a EGF family growth factor.

982
00:56:34.204 --> 00:56:37.904
And these concentrate in these spaces and very absolutely required

983
00:56:37.964 --> 00:56:41.924
for metastasis. And so what's really remarkable here is

984
00:56:41.964 --> 00:56:45.564
that clusters then, not only are immuno ecosystems, but also

985
00:56:45.604 --> 00:56:49.204
produce factors that allow them to carry their own local

986
00:56:49.264 --> 00:56:53.004
microenvironments that manifest as useful for metastatic colonization.

987
00:56:54.204 --> 00:56:57.664
Altogether, in the field, I think we've become very interested in this notion of a

988
00:56:57.684 --> 00:57:01.084
collective model of metastasis, where clusters, as we know and the pathologists

989
00:57:01.124 --> 00:57:03.704
appreciate, can invade blood and lymphatic vessels.

990
00:57:04.224 --> 00:57:08.144
And over a course of months to years, these clusters are found across

991
00:57:08.184 --> 00:57:11.844
the stages of metastatic progression, and in large numbers can allow for

992
00:57:11.884 --> 00:57:14.144
polyclonal seeding, genetic heterogeneity,

993
00:57:14.964 --> 00:57:18.524
overcome a variety of bottlenecks in the metastatic process, and even

994
00:57:18.584 --> 00:57:22.464
can cause direct injury to vital organs such as the brain,

995
00:57:22.964 --> 00:57:23.764
the lung, liver,

996
00:57:24.984 --> 00:57:26.444
perhaps even to the heart.

997
00:57:27.254 --> 00:57:31.064
And these emergent properties involve a variety of increasing resistance

998
00:57:31.524 --> 00:57:34.644
to immunologic and seer stress, detachment, metastatic

999
00:57:34.664 --> 00:57:38.584
potential, and involves the transport

1000
00:57:38.824 --> 00:57:42.524
a variety of cell and sort of ecosystem components.

1001
00:57:43.884 --> 00:57:47.624
Now, in my lab, we became interested in necrosis by asking the question, what are

1002
00:57:47.664 --> 00:57:50.644
the microenvironmental forces that drive collective tumor dissemination?

1003
00:57:50.704 --> 00:57:53.524
This is work really led by a very talented graduate student in my lab, Ami

1004
00:57:53.584 --> 00:57:56.264
Yamamoto, who's now since in industry.

1005
00:57:56.944 --> 00:58:00.464
And this really begins with sort of a clinical study that we performed really

1006
00:58:00.504 --> 00:58:04.364
during the COVID era, trying to understand what are the factors

1007
00:58:04.404 --> 00:58:07.164
associated with sort of circulating tumor cell dissemination.

1008
00:58:07.194 --> 00:58:10.584
And what we found in our patients at the Fred Hutch is that you could find these

1009
00:58:10.624 --> 00:58:14.444
single CCCs and CTC clusters. And as

1010
00:58:14.484 --> 00:58:18.264
has been seen by a number of other studies, the presence of CTCs and CTC

1011
00:58:18.324 --> 00:58:21.544
clusters is a very sort of negative prognostic

1012
00:58:22.084 --> 00:58:25.824
feature. And particularly for CTC clusters, within even a few months,

1013
00:58:26.344 --> 00:58:27.004
many of the patients

1014
00:58:27.844 --> 00:58:31.684
had to go into hospice or no longer had any therapy that would benefit

1015
00:58:31.704 --> 00:58:31.844
them.

1016
00:58:33.124 --> 00:58:36.364
But when we looked more closely, also we found that there were some really unusual

1017
00:58:36.444 --> 00:58:40.184
CTC dynamics. And in particular, we could see that CTCs rised

1018
00:58:40.224 --> 00:58:40.824
acutely.

1019
00:58:41.644 --> 00:58:45.144
In this case, you see CA 15-3 is a blood marker, LDH.

1020
00:58:45.504 --> 00:58:49.244
CTCs rise, in this case, up to 1,000 from a very low number.

1021
00:58:49.364 --> 00:58:52.394
CTC clusters rise. And in this patient,

1022
00:58:52.484 --> 00:58:56.404
basically very soon after, they were admitted for liver injury and tumor

1023
00:58:56.424 --> 00:59:00.284
lysis. And when we look at the CT scan, when you have a very high, from low to high

1024
00:59:00.344 --> 00:59:04.104
CTC transition, you see emergence of this necrosis on the

1025
00:59:04.204 --> 00:59:05.904
actual scan. This is a sort of a

1026
00:59:07.064 --> 00:59:10.984
multi capturing CT scan that allows us to look at the

1027
00:59:11.004 --> 00:59:11.584
microenvironment.

1028
00:59:13.104 --> 00:59:16.664
When we looked at sort of the proteomics of the patients who had these

1029
00:59:16.804 --> 00:59:20.464
acute rises in CTCs, interestingly, we saw acute

1030
00:59:20.843 --> 00:59:24.564
rise in proteins associated with lactic acid metabolism and also proteins

1031
00:59:24.944 --> 00:59:28.724
associated with cell death. And this was one of the first clues that, in fact,

1032
00:59:28.864 --> 00:59:32.064
CTCs are somehow coupled to

1033
00:59:32.104 --> 00:59:33.684
death-associated proteins.

1034
00:59:34.654 --> 00:59:37.174
And so we wanted to study this more closely in animal model.

1035
00:59:37.224 --> 00:59:40.924
And as you know, many in the audience who study mouse models of cancer,

1036
00:59:41.624 --> 00:59:44.964
mice individually do not have a lot of blood volume between 0.5 to 1 mil.

1037
00:59:45.904 --> 00:59:49.624
Humans, we can draw 10 mils in a draw, which is actually only a small

1038
00:59:49.684 --> 00:59:52.824
fraction of the five liters in the entire system.

1039
00:59:52.944 --> 00:59:56.624
We became interested in using rats because they are much more

1040
00:59:56.984 --> 01:00:00.404
robust as a system to obtain 5 to 10 mils of blood.

1041
01:00:00.444 --> 01:00:04.344
And what we found using the common 4T1 model, as Jose

1042
01:00:04.404 --> 01:00:08.264
also used earlier, is that if you implant the same number of cells into NSG mice or

1043
01:00:08.384 --> 01:00:09.924
SRG immunocompromised rats,

1044
01:00:10.724 --> 01:00:14.684
we could very cleanly, with microscopy, identify individual CTCs and

1045
01:00:14.724 --> 01:00:18.644
CTC clusters. And we could obtain, in an individual animal, 10 times more

1046
01:00:18.664 --> 01:00:20.854
CTCs than in a comparable mouse.

1047
01:00:21.824 --> 01:00:25.164
And why this is important, because then we can start to ask the question, on an

1048
01:00:25.224 --> 01:00:28.024
individual animal basis, what are the dynamics?

1049
01:00:28.164 --> 01:00:31.024
What are the causes and factors that give rise to CTC induction?

1050
01:00:31.844 --> 01:00:32.444
So when we looked at the

1051
01:00:33.264 --> 01:00:36.524
CTC dynamics, what we arrived at was something unusual.

1052
01:00:36.544 --> 01:00:39.784
We expected in this sort of animal experiment, days

1053
01:00:39.844 --> 01:00:41.844
post-transplantation, to have a continuous rise.

1054
01:00:41.924 --> 01:00:45.524
But what we saw actually was this acute jump between day 22 and 27.

1055
01:00:46.004 --> 01:00:49.444
This kind of hockey stick phenomena suggests that CTC is bursting.

1056
01:00:50.144 --> 01:00:53.204
And we want to understand more closely what is happening in this sort of CT

1057
01:00:53.504 --> 01:00:54.474
transition phase.

1058
01:00:55.324 --> 01:00:59.034
Working with our colleague, Mike Hafner, a very talented pathologist, he said,

1059
01:00:59.234 --> 01:01:00.904
"Kevin, we look at the edges of these tumors.

1060
01:01:00.924 --> 01:01:03.194
They look identical from day 13 to day 27.

1061
01:01:03.414 --> 01:01:05.344
There's nothing different about the tumor edge.

1062
01:01:05.364 --> 01:01:07.764
But what's clearly different is that there's a lot more necrosis.

1063
01:01:08.164 --> 01:01:10.624
There's a lot more cell death inside these tumors.

1064
01:01:10.684 --> 01:01:14.474
And really, this necrotic area very strongly increases between day 22 and

1065
01:01:14.584 --> 01:01:18.406
27."And here's an example of a very classic,

1066
01:01:18.756 --> 01:01:21.936
you can use a TTZ assay, a trypan blue chloride assay.

1067
01:01:22.036 --> 01:01:25.336
Red is the viable tissue. Yellow marks the dead tissue.

1068
01:01:25.376 --> 01:01:29.316
And this is a sort of myocardial infarction heart attack.

1069
01:01:29.716 --> 01:01:30.776
You can see very similar sort of

1070
01:01:31.816 --> 01:01:35.036
kinetics here. Day 20, you see there's mostly viable.

1071
01:01:35.296 --> 01:01:38.396
By day 24, you see these large confluent zones.

1072
01:01:39.196 --> 01:01:43.036
I do think that, as Jose brought up, there is microscopic, and we'll talk

1073
01:01:43.056 --> 01:01:46.936
about it later, small areas necrosis, but these do progressively

1074
01:01:46.976 --> 01:01:50.896
become confluent and dominant. And when you look at tumors later on, although

1075
01:01:50.936 --> 01:01:53.216
the tumors are growing, a lot of it is dead.

1076
01:01:54.996 --> 01:01:58.296
And what's really interesting here is on a per animal basis, we found that the

1077
01:01:58.356 --> 01:02:01.996
number of lung metastases shown you in the x-axis was highly correlated with the

1078
01:02:02.016 --> 01:02:05.426
amount of necrosis, not with total tumor size.

1079
01:02:05.936 --> 01:02:08.376
And so what this says is that there's a component of chance here.

1080
01:02:08.996 --> 01:02:12.736
Some tumors develop necrosis. The ones that develop necrosis

1081
01:02:13.036 --> 01:02:14.436
are the ones that develop metastatic cancer.

1082
01:02:15.756 --> 01:02:19.196
One other thing we noticed was that in close association with

1083
01:02:19.236 --> 01:02:22.156
necrosis was the presence of these dilated blood vessels.

1084
01:02:22.536 --> 01:02:25.956
Blood vessels that appear to be penetrating into the necrotic zone from the sort of

1085
01:02:25.996 --> 01:02:26.856
perinecrotic region.

1086
01:02:27.756 --> 01:02:31.666
Quite dilated. And in particular, when we look more closely at these

1087
01:02:31.676 --> 01:02:35.666
dilated vessels, we could find evidence of tumor cell clusters and tumor cells in

1088
01:02:35.696 --> 01:02:39.416
these intravascular zones. This is really remarkable because

1089
01:02:39.456 --> 01:02:42.656
necrosis is happening a lot of times deep within the tumor.

1090
01:02:43.156 --> 01:02:47.036
These we're talking about between many millimeters to even centimeters in these

1091
01:02:47.076 --> 01:02:50.996
rat tumors. This is really pretty far from the tumor edge, and yet we see

1092
01:02:51.036 --> 01:02:54.336
there's a mechanism by which these cells get in there.

1093
01:02:54.376 --> 01:02:58.136
So what these data thus far tell us that necrotic transition is closely associated

1094
01:02:58.156 --> 01:03:00.936
with CTC and CT cluster dissemination in patients and animal models.

1095
01:03:02.236 --> 01:03:04.216
I want to focus now on two questions.

1096
01:03:04.596 --> 01:03:06.896
How can a dead necrotic core cause dissemination?

1097
01:03:07.556 --> 01:03:10.136
And are tumor cells passive bystanders in this process?

1098
01:03:11.436 --> 01:03:13.026
We performed RNA expression analysis.

1099
01:03:13.136 --> 01:03:17.036
This is basically using, like in this case, SRG rats, 421 is a mouse

1100
01:03:17.476 --> 01:03:20.436
line. We're able to do some RNA seq deconvolution.

1101
01:03:20.456 --> 01:03:24.136
It's nothing fancy. As you might expect,

1102
01:03:24.806 --> 01:03:27.756
there's both tumor and host-derived transcriptional changes.

1103
01:03:28.696 --> 01:03:32.416
But this is really interesting because it turns out that the tumor itself in these

1104
01:03:32.476 --> 01:03:35.496
core regions produce their own distinct sets of proteins.

1105
01:03:35.536 --> 01:03:38.256
This was a question brought up by someone in the audience.

1106
01:03:38.716 --> 01:03:42.596
In this case, we found that the top protein being expressed was this protein

1107
01:03:42.616 --> 01:03:45.676
called angiopoietin-like 7. It's a member of this angiopoietin-like family.

1108
01:03:45.836 --> 01:03:49.356
Other members are FDA-approved drug targets in

1109
01:03:49.456 --> 01:03:53.045
cardiovascular indications. And what we see here is a strong

1110
01:03:53.116 --> 01:03:56.726
induction in the core but not in the rim, and it's a tumor-derived, not a

1111
01:03:56.736 --> 01:03:58.556
host-derived factor. This is a common issue.

1112
01:03:58.756 --> 01:04:00.636
You might go after a drug target,

1113
01:04:01.436 --> 01:04:04.576
but if it's both tumor and host-derived, it's going to be a little bit messy to

1114
01:04:04.616 --> 01:04:08.296
figure out what's going on. Here's clearly this is a tumor-derived

1115
01:04:08.306 --> 01:04:08.746
protein.

1116
01:04:09.836 --> 01:04:13.236
And we can see very nicely by, in this case, RNA fish, shown here in green,

1117
01:04:13.916 --> 01:04:17.816
that the regions are necrotic, and then the red is the angiopoietin-like 7

1118
01:04:17.976 --> 01:04:20.476
RNA fish spots, and you can see that it's enriched in the core.

1119
01:04:21.796 --> 01:04:24.056
Now, one of the things that we found was this chicken or the egg.

1120
01:04:24.136 --> 01:04:27.896
Well, it turns out when we knock down angiopoietin-like 7 in the

1121
01:04:27.936 --> 01:04:30.736
tumor cells, we drastically reduce necrosis.

1122
01:04:31.176 --> 01:04:33.376
So necrosis is actually a preventable process.

1123
01:04:34.256 --> 01:04:36.786
Knockdown also reduces dilated vessel abundance.

1124
01:04:37.576 --> 01:04:41.456
And also further, suppression of angiopoietin-7 basically takes CTC

1125
01:04:41.496 --> 01:04:44.796
dissemination down close to zero in the

1126
01:04:45.216 --> 01:04:48.696
strongest knockdowns in both single CTCs and CTC clusters.

1127
01:04:49.316 --> 01:04:53.236
So in fact, the tumor cells are producing a factor which is regulating

1128
01:04:53.316 --> 01:04:55.246
CTC and CTC cluster dissemination.

1129
01:04:56.656 --> 01:05:00.116
These also lead to downstream reductions in lung metastasis.

1130
01:05:00.216 --> 01:05:03.116
So how can a dead necrotic zone cause dissemination?

1131
01:05:03.156 --> 01:05:06.376
Well, there are viable perinecrotic tumor cells engaging the tumor

1132
01:05:06.756 --> 01:05:09.756
necrotic zone. And are tumor cells passive bystanders

1133
01:05:11.156 --> 01:05:14.736
in this process? Well, our data would suggest the tumor cells actively

1134
01:05:14.756 --> 01:05:18.126
produce proteins which promote necrotic core transition.

1135
01:05:19.616 --> 01:05:23.096
So with the time remaining, I wanted to focus on some of our

1136
01:05:23.136 --> 01:05:26.545
unpublished work to understand what are the cellular and molecular

1137
01:05:26.636 --> 01:05:29.076
architecture of tumor necrosis in human cancer patients.

1138
01:05:29.436 --> 01:05:33.295
As I talked about in the beginning of this session, this is

1139
01:05:33.396 --> 01:05:36.735
oftentimes an area of the tumor which we kind of actively

1140
01:05:36.795 --> 01:05:40.036
ignore because our expectation is that the cells are dead.

1141
01:05:40.056 --> 01:05:43.986
But as the other presenters have really nicely shown, there's a lot of interesting

1142
01:05:44.036 --> 01:05:44.566
biology there.

1143
01:05:45.886 --> 01:05:47.976
And so working closely with our colleague, Christopher Lee,

1144
01:05:49.276 --> 01:05:52.996
and his statistical analyst, and also Rebecca Alvarez in

1145
01:05:53.056 --> 01:05:56.656
UW Breast Pathology, we employed Christopher's

1146
01:05:57.536 --> 01:06:01.516
Bravo study, which is basically over 4,000 breast cancer patients recruited

1147
01:06:01.576 --> 01:06:05.496
in the Washington State area, was oversampling for different breast

1148
01:06:05.516 --> 01:06:06.416
cancer subtypes.

1149
01:06:07.256 --> 01:06:09.276
There's over 1,500 triple negative cases.

1150
01:06:09.936 --> 01:06:13.796
And they're really able then to use these kind of case matching to get really good

1151
01:06:14.496 --> 01:06:18.206
matched cases that differ really only between those that recur and do not

1152
01:06:18.236 --> 01:06:18.516
recur.

1153
01:06:19.356 --> 01:06:23.026
Focusing on 140 of these cases over 800 slides, we then,

1154
01:06:23.356 --> 01:06:27.106
Rebecca and her colleagues, have reviewed these slides for lymphovascular

1155
01:06:27.116 --> 01:06:30.676
invasion, necrosis, dilated vessels, and their spatial location.

1156
01:06:31.016 --> 01:06:34.776
And so our goal was to understand the association between each of these histologic

1157
01:06:34.856 --> 01:06:38.436
features with clinical pathologic features and clinical outcome.

1158
01:06:39.356 --> 01:06:40.016
Now, what did we find?

1159
01:06:41.456 --> 01:06:45.386
We were really surprised. So when Rebecca looked at these

1160
01:06:45.496 --> 01:06:48.856
slides, she came back and said to me, "Hey, Kevin, it's a little more complicated

1161
01:06:48.866 --> 01:06:52.066
than you might have imagined. It's not just necrosis or no necrosis.

1162
01:06:52.576 --> 01:06:55.736
In fact, there are different histologies that coexist in the same breast

1163
01:06:55.776 --> 01:06:59.676
tumor." This is an example of a central necrosis

1164
01:06:59.716 --> 01:07:01.976
region in a triple negative tumor.

1165
01:07:01.996 --> 01:07:05.336
But what we can see very clearly is there are regions with high amounts of

1166
01:07:05.376 --> 01:07:09.316
coagulative necrosis and also areas with what we call reparative changes,

1167
01:07:10.136 --> 01:07:13.056
things that are commonly associated with what we call wound repair.

1168
01:07:14.636 --> 01:07:18.476
Now, what's interesting is these coagulative necrosis reparative changes are

1169
01:07:18.516 --> 01:07:20.216
highly associated with each other.

1170
01:07:20.536 --> 01:07:24.286
So the more coagulative necrosis you have, the more reparative changes, but

1171
01:07:24.356 --> 01:07:27.796
not totally just sort of on a one-to-one

1172
01:07:27.816 --> 01:07:31.492
basis.One of the interesting thing is coagul necrosis was inversely

1173
01:07:31.532 --> 01:07:35.032
associated with lymphovascular invasion which is occurring outside the tumor.

1174
01:07:35.432 --> 01:07:39.252
So in fact, these might be perhaps linked in some way, which we don't fully

1175
01:07:39.272 --> 01:07:43.202
understand yet and these reparative changes often directly

1176
01:07:43.232 --> 01:07:45.622
were adjacent to a coagulum necrosis, but not

1177
01:07:45.692 --> 01:07:49.632
always. But what's really interesting is that it turns out

1178
01:07:49.792 --> 01:07:53.312
from a prognostic implications standpoint, they seem to differ.

1179
01:07:53.772 --> 01:07:57.432
Coagulum necrosis was not particularly prognostic whereas

1180
01:07:57.472 --> 01:07:59.352
reparative changes were highly prognostic.

1181
01:07:59.592 --> 01:08:01.842
5% or more of the tumor having reparative changes

1182
01:08:02.252 --> 01:08:05.512
basically predicted much worse prognosis,

1183
01:08:06.472 --> 01:08:09.502
and this was highly prognostic for breast cancer recurrence, all-cause

1184
01:08:09.572 --> 01:08:13.232
mortality, and breast cancer specific mortality, including when you

1185
01:08:13.292 --> 01:08:16.952
adjust for a variety of sort of key factors associated with, including tumor

1186
01:08:17.032 --> 01:08:20.132
stage, age, and competing non-breast cancer death.

1187
01:08:21.833 --> 01:08:25.352
Furthermore, and particularly interesting for us, thinking about how these might be

1188
01:08:25.392 --> 01:08:29.352
deployed in the future in a clinical setting, we found the reparative changes

1189
01:08:29.392 --> 01:08:33.092
in lymphovascular invasion were independently prognostic and identify a

1190
01:08:33.132 --> 01:08:37.062
high-risk triple negative subgroup that with both LVI and high

1191
01:08:37.132 --> 01:08:40.592
reparative, had very early recurrences in the triple negative

1192
01:08:40.632 --> 01:08:43.172
population, and much worse mortality.

1193
01:08:43.213 --> 01:08:44.873
And this was highly significant,

1194
01:08:45.772 --> 01:08:48.913
with a hazard ratio up to five.

1195
01:08:50.102 --> 01:08:53.992
So this is really exciting to us because it tells us that tumor necrosis

1196
01:08:54.012 --> 01:08:57.772
is not one state, but multiple states, and what we see, in fact, is a

1197
01:08:57.812 --> 01:08:59.232
history of a dynamic process.

1198
01:09:00.293 --> 01:09:04.192
You look at... This is Apollo Moon mission image, maybe timely

1199
01:09:04.232 --> 01:09:08.172
in the news, and the point is that you can see the craters

1200
01:09:08.192 --> 01:09:11.753
here reflect the different ages, the history of many events.

1201
01:09:12.312 --> 01:09:15.833
And when we look more closely with our pathologist, we see evidence

